WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.750 --> 00:00:11.750
Hi everyone, I'm Stefan from the Flugschule Frewings flight school, and today I want to talk a bit about aerodynamics.

2
00:00:11.750 --> 00:00:17.900
Aerodynamics in general, but above all paraglider-specific.

3
00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:22.900
The question that surely concerns all of us — how does a paraglider actually fly?

4
00:00:22.900 --> 00:00:29.900
Ever since the first moment as a kid, when I saw a paraglider launch, I couldn't let go of it — I've always been fascinated.

5
00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:36.900
How can it be that a wing made from a bit of fabric and a few lines, pulled out of a backpack,

6
00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:40.900
lifts us into the air — how can you fly with this thing?

7
00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:48.450
And once you dig into the basics, you quickly find out that a paraglider works exactly the same way.

8
00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:56.450
Like an aeroplane, like a bird too — we have a wing surface that generates lift, and through that produces a force

9
00:00:56.450 --> 00:00:58.450
that keeps us up in the air.

10
00:00:58.450 --> 00:01:01.450
I'll compare it a bit to a car.

11
00:01:01.450 --> 00:01:09.450
Everyone can drive a car, but if you really understand how the clutch and the engine and everything works in detail,

12
00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:12.450
that's often quite decisive.

13
00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:19.640
With the paraglider it can also happen that you're a super top pilot and don't really know

14
00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:22.640
what's actually going on above you.

15
00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:27.640
But I'm of the opinion that this is relatively important for paragliding.

16
00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:30.640
Maybe more so than for driving a car.

17
00:01:30.640 --> 00:01:33.640
So that you understand the technical background a little bit,

18
00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:41.640
because it matters for safety, and also when you want to get the full performance out of the wing,

19
00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:45.640
when later on you fly a bit more ambitiously and things get serious.

20
00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:52.640
Having that background helps, because you'll also want to get more out of the wing.

21
00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:57.500
It all started a very, very long time ago.

22
00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:03.500
Otto Lilienthal started back in 1891

23
00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:08.500
and he built the very first — you could almost say — hang gliders,

24
00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:12.500
and he carried out the first successful flights.

25
00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:17.500
Even earlier he'd started observing birds, and he noticed

26
00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:22.500
that not every bird needs to flap its wings to stay in the air.

27
00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:25.500
Above all he looked at the larger birds

28
00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.500
and noticed they can do this really well —

29
00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:30.500
they glide without doing anything with their wings.

30
00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:34.500
Then he started — with storks from the Rhineland —

31
00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:38.500
to dissect the animals and observed

32
00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:45.500
that the wings of all these animals showed a certain airfoil profile.

33
00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:51.500
And he then transferred that wing profile onto his own wings.

34
00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:54.500
And then he discovered that you generate lift this way,

35
00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:56.500
when the air flows in,

36
00:02:56.500 --> 00:03:02.860
the air carries you, after taking a few running steps.

37
00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:06.860
In general there are several different attempts to explain

38
00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:09.860
or reasons why a wing flies.

39
00:03:10.860 --> 00:03:14.860
Basically there are three approaches or three principles

40
00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:19.860
for how a wing generates lift and keeps us up in the air.

41
00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:23.860
The first approach is Bernoulli's theory.

42
00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:27.180
We're dealing here with flow dynamics.

43
00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:30.180
We have a wing profile here,

44
00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:32.180
like most wing profiles.

45
00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:35.180
They're asymmetric, meaning on top

46
00:03:35.180 --> 00:03:38.180
we have a larger curvature than underneath.

47
00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:45.180
That causes the airflow on top to have to circulate faster,

48
00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:49.180
to flow faster, and there you get a low pressure.

49
00:03:49.180 --> 00:03:52.180
Before that, it comes in from the front.

50
00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:55.180
(unclear)

51
00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:58.340
(unclear)

52
00:03:58.340 --> 00:04:01.340
(unclear)

53
00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:05.340
(unclear)

54
00:04:06.340 --> 00:04:08.340
(unclear)

55
00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:08.900
(unclear)

56
00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:11.380
(unclear)

57
00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:14.340
(unclear)

58
00:04:16.340 --> 00:04:18.340
(unclear)

59
00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:22.700
which creates a force acting on us.

60
00:04:22.700 --> 00:04:26.700
The distribution is another little detail for the theory exam.

61
00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:29.700
The distribution is two-thirds low pressure on the upper surface

62
00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:33.700
and one-third high pressure on the underside of the wing.

63
00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:36.700
It's a bit confusing in terms of the wording,

64
00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:38.920
and you have to make sure you don't mix it up.

65
00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:41.920
At some point the airflow begins

66
00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:44.920
to follow the profile and then to detach from it.

67
00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:46.920
That's called the separation point,

68
00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:50.920
where a little turbulence and a bit of drag is generated.

69
00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:53.920
But we'll come back to that

70
00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:55.920
in more detail later.

71
00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:59.920
Basically: Bernoulli's theory, flow dynamics, low pressure, high pressure —

72
00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:01.920
that's the first approach.

73
00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:03.920
How does a wing fly?

74
00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:06.920
The second one is the recoil principle.

75
00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:10.080
That's action-equals-reaction from Newton,

76
00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:12.080
who figured out

77
00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:14.080
that on every body,

78
00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:18.080
when any force is applied, an opposing force arises.

79
00:05:18.080 --> 00:05:21.080
You may have tried this yourself,

80
00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:24.080
when you stick your hand out of a moving car.

81
00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:26.080
Maybe not as the driver —

82
00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:28.080
maybe once as a passenger,

83
00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:31.080
and pay attention to exactly what happens

84
00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:33.080
when you hold your hand out straight.

85
00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:34.080
Not much happens —

86
00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:35.080
you've probably felt that —

87
00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:37.080
there's no big resistance,

88
00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:39.080
because the hand surface is along the wind.

89
00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:41.080
When you start angling your hand,

90
00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:45.080
in one direction there's a force that pulls upward.

91
00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:47.080
And if you tilt it the other way,

92
00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:49.080
then your hand gets pushed downward.

93
00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:53.080
And the wing uses this recoil principle too,

94
00:05:53.080 --> 00:05:56.080
because in the wing there's also a certain angle

95
00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:58.080
to the incoming airflow.

96
00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:00.080
We call this the angle of attack —

97
00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:02.080
we'll come back to that later.

98
00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:03.080
And it creates a force

99
00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:05.080
that points upward

100
00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:08.780
and keeps us up in the air.

101
00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:10.780
The third approach

102
00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:12.780
for how a wing produces lift

103
00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:15.780
is the so-called circulation flow.

104
00:06:15.780 --> 00:06:19.780
At the sharp trailing edge of the wing,

105
00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:22.040
a starting vortex develops.

106
00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:25.040
And the flow is then deflected downward.

107
00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:28.040
And there again you get a moment

108
00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:30.040
or force pointing upward,

109
00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:34.040
which also contributes to dynamic lift.

110
00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:36.460
Those are the three principles

111
00:06:36.460 --> 00:06:39.460
that keep the wing in the air.

112
00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:44.460
Now we have a few technical terms

113
00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:46.460
around wing profiles too.

114
00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:48.460
Right now we're still looking at the wing

115
00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:50.460
in cross-section.

116
00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:53.460
Later we'll look at the whole paraglider,

117
00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:56.460
the entire wing across the span as well,

118
00:06:56.460 --> 00:06:58.460
and also the lines and the pilot,

119
00:06:58.460 --> 00:07:00.460
the pilot hanging underneath,

120
00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.460
and what influence all that has.

121
00:07:02.460 --> 00:07:05.650
For the moment we're just looking at the cross-section.

122
00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:07.650
With the paraglider,

123
00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:09.650
the profile is relatively thick.

124
00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:12.650
So the profile thickness — that's the blue bar.

125
00:07:12.650 --> 00:07:14.650
It's relatively thick.

126
00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:18.650
Compared, for example, to a fast aircraft,

127
00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:19.650
to a fighter jet,

128
00:07:19.650 --> 00:07:21.650
where the profile is very flat

129
00:07:21.650 --> 00:07:23.650
and not very asymmetric,

130
00:07:23.650 --> 00:07:25.650
and rather thinner.

131
00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:27.650
So a slow aircraft,

132
00:07:27.650 --> 00:07:30.650
which at low takeoff speed

133
00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:32.650
already generates a lot of lift,

134
00:07:32.650 --> 00:07:35.650
without needing a huge speed

135
00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:38.650
to produce or generate it.

136
00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:40.650
It's mostly a thick

137
00:07:40.650 --> 00:07:42.650
and asymmetric profile that's chosen.

138
00:07:42.650 --> 00:07:44.650
Profile depth is essentially the distance

139
00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:47.650
from the front stagnation point to the rear stagnation point.

140
00:07:47.650 --> 00:07:48.650
On the paraglider,

141
00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:50.650
that's the leading edge and the trailing edge,

142
00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:51.650
where you can see

143
00:07:51.650 --> 00:07:52.650
these are terms

144
00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:54.650
you'll need again and again with aircraft.

145
00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:58.650
Profile chord is a theoretical concept.

146
00:07:58.650 --> 00:07:59.650
It's the connecting line

147
00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:01.650
from the front to the back.

148
00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:04.650
Don't confuse it with profile depth.

149
00:08:04.650 --> 00:08:07.650
Profile depth is just the distance, and profile chord

150
00:08:07.650 --> 00:08:10.650
is really the connecting line between the two points.

151
00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:14.860
Now we can move on to forces and vectors.

152
00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:16.860
I briefly mentioned earlier

153
00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:20.860
that several force vectors act on the wing

154
00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:25.860
through lift and drag — all of these together combine

155
00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:27.860
into one main vector,

156
00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:29.860
the lift vector.

157
00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:31.860
Or later we'll learn

158
00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:34.860
that's then the aerodynamic resultant,

159
00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:38.860
which is composed of lift and drag.

160
00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:40.860
But more on that later.

161
00:08:40.860 --> 00:08:42.860
First of all, just theoretically,

162
00:08:42.860 --> 00:08:45.060
how that looks with vectors —

163
00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:48.060
this is a classic theory exam question.

164
00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:50.060
It works like this:

165
00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:51.060
when you want

166
00:08:51.060 --> 00:08:52.060
to combine forces,

167
00:08:52.060 --> 00:08:55.060
or when at the same application point on a body

168
00:08:55.060 --> 00:08:58.060
two different forces act,

169
00:08:58.060 --> 00:09:01.060
then you can hang the forces onto each other.

170
00:09:01.060 --> 00:09:03.060
We see here in the example

171
00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:07.060
forces F1 and F4 acting on a body.

172
00:09:07.060 --> 00:09:09.060
They have the same application point.

173
00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:12.060
What is the resultant R of the two forces?

174
00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:15.060
So on the left we have F1 and F4,

175
00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:17.060
we pick those up,

176
00:09:17.060 --> 00:09:19.060
then we have to hang them onto each other.

177
00:09:19.060 --> 00:09:21.060
And see what the result is.

178
00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:24.180
And if we now go from the start point to the end point

179
00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:26.180
of F1,

180
00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:28.180
and add F4

181
00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:32.180
and then from the start point of both to the end point,

182
00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:33.180
we connect them,

183
00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:35.180
then we see the result —

184
00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:37.180
a diagonal force

185
00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:40.180
that's changed level a bit.

186
00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:42.180
It's the sum of these two forces,

187
00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:45.180
and in this example it's R2.

188
00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:51.830
Then we have another example.

189
00:09:51.830 --> 00:09:54.830
If the forces act in the same direction,

190
00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:56.830
then of course it's even simpler.

191
00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:58.830
Then there's no diagonal or anything,

192
00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:00.830
you can just add the forces up,

193
00:10:00.830 --> 00:10:03.830
for example we can count the squares here

194
00:10:03.830 --> 00:10:05.830
and see F1 plus F2,

195
00:10:05.830 --> 00:10:07.830
4 squares plus 2 squares,

196
00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:09.830
gives 6 squares for R3.

197
00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:12.150
Then we can also see

198
00:10:12.150 --> 00:10:14.150
what happens when the forces act in opposite directions.

199
00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:18.150
And now suppose the forces are exactly the same size.

200
00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:20.150
We have some stone

201
00:10:20.150 --> 00:10:22.150
and from both sides some force pushes it,

202
00:10:22.150 --> 00:10:24.150
and if they're exactly equal,

203
00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:27.150
then the stone stays exactly in place.

204
00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:30.440
And here we see F1

205
00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:34.440
is smaller, so F3 deviates a bit there.

206
00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:36.440
And again we combine them.

207
00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:38.440
Now you can sum the forces up

208
00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:40.440
and together it gives R4.

209
00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:46.000
This basic knowledge is still important

210
00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
for understanding the next few slides.

211
00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Here we have again a wing, profile chord,

212
00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
in the drawing, which is aerodynamically quite important.

213
00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
We'll see the whole thing in a moment —

214
00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
we have the aerodynamic resultant,

215
00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
which I briefly mentioned earlier.

216
00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.310
We have lift and drag.

217
00:11:06.310 --> 00:11:08.310
The absolute dream case would of course be

218
00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:10.310
to build a wing

219
00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:12.310
that produces no drag.

220
00:11:12.310 --> 00:11:13.310
So no air resistance.

221
00:11:13.310 --> 00:11:15.310
But that's just not possible,

222
00:11:15.310 --> 00:11:17.310
because we have a certain frontal area,

223
00:11:17.310 --> 00:11:18.310
a certain surface

224
00:11:18.310 --> 00:11:20.310
that the air has to push against.

225
00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:22.310
And that always generates drag.

226
00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:25.310
We can build as perfect a wing as we like.

227
00:11:25.310 --> 00:11:27.310
We will never fully get rid of

228
00:11:27.310 --> 00:11:30.310
the drag force that acts against us.

229
00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:32.310
And lift and drag

230
00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:33.310
combined.

231
00:11:33.310 --> 00:11:34.310
We see here too,

232
00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:36.310
they form a triangle.

233
00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:37.310
And the diagonal of that

234
00:11:37.310 --> 00:11:40.310
is the aerodynamic resultant.

235
00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:41.540
What's important —

236
00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:43.540
shown on the left —

237
00:11:43.540 --> 00:11:45.540
lift and drag

238
00:11:45.540 --> 00:11:47.540
are always at 90° to each other.

239
00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:48.540
Not sometimes,

240
00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:51.540
but always exactly at 90°.

241
00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:53.540
Drag is always exactly

242
00:11:53.540 --> 00:11:56.540
in line with the incoming airflow,

243
00:11:56.540 --> 00:12:01.540
so with the flight path or with the airflow.

244
00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:03.540
It always comes down to the colour,

245
00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:04.540
as you can see.

246
00:12:04.540 --> 00:12:06.540
It doesn't really play a role

247
00:12:06.540 --> 00:12:08.540
whether the wing is in a wind tunnel

248
00:12:08.540 --> 00:12:10.540
for a theoretical setup, or whether the wing

249
00:12:10.540 --> 00:12:12.540
is gliding through still air.

250
00:12:12.540 --> 00:12:14.540
Above all, it's always relative:

251
00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:17.880
the wing relative to the air.

252
00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:21.230
The centre of pressure is also important —

253
00:12:21.230 --> 00:12:23.230
don't forget the centre of pressure.

254
00:12:23.230 --> 00:12:24.230
It's the point

255
00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:26.230
where all these forces act.

256
00:12:26.230 --> 00:12:28.230
And weight force

257
00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:30.230
is always equal in size

258
00:12:30.230 --> 00:12:32.230
to the aerodynamic resultant.

259
00:12:32.230 --> 00:12:34.230
So if we're heavier,

260
00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:36.230
we need more lift,

261
00:12:36.230 --> 00:12:37.230
more drag.

262
00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:40.230
And the aerodynamic resultant grows too.

263
00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:47.420
Now let's continue with this slide.

264
00:12:47.420 --> 00:12:49.420
With the airflow direction

265
00:12:49.420 --> 00:12:51.420
I mentioned briefly,

266
00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:52.420
the airflow direction,

267
00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:54.420
which runs in exactly the same direction

268
00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:55.420
as the drag.

269
00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:57.420
And here you can see the airflow now.

270
00:12:57.420 --> 00:12:59.420
Here's the hand,

271
00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:00.420
held a bit at an angle,

272
00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:02.420
tilted a bit in this air channel

273
00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:05.420
or in an airflow.

274
00:13:35.830 --> 00:13:38.830
Let's look at neutral, unmoving, still air masses.

275
00:13:38.830 --> 00:13:39.830
Let's look at that.

276
00:13:39.830 --> 00:13:45.830
Then we can move on to the drag

277
00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:46.830
of a body.

278
00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:49.830
There's another interesting formula

279
00:13:49.830 --> 00:13:51.830
for drag and lift.

280
00:13:51.830 --> 00:13:52.830
They're always exactly

281
00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:55.830
the same — at the front we have W for drag.

282
00:13:55.830 --> 00:13:58.830
After that we have a few factors

283
00:13:58.830 --> 00:14:00.830
that produce the drag.

284
00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:02.830
Very important here,

285
00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:03.830
please don't get scared.

286
00:14:03.830 --> 00:14:05.830
For the theory exam,

287
00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:07.830
the brevet theory exam,

288
00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:09.830
you don't have to memorise any formulas

289
00:14:09.830 --> 00:14:11.830
and you don't have to be able to compute in this style.

290
00:14:11.830 --> 00:14:13.830
So don't be scared.

291
00:14:13.830 --> 00:14:15.830
I've only drawn the formula

292
00:14:15.830 --> 00:14:16.830
to show

293
00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:18.830
which elements

294
00:14:18.830 --> 00:14:20.830
actually combine to produce drag,

295
00:14:20.830 --> 00:14:21.830
what it consists of.

296
00:14:21.830 --> 00:14:23.830
First of all we have C.

297
00:14:23.830 --> 00:14:26.220
That's the shape and the angle of attack.

298
00:14:26.220 --> 00:14:28.220
And here it comes down to

299
00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:29.220
whether it's a wing,

300
00:14:29.220 --> 00:14:31.220
or a car, or some rock in the wind.

301
00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:34.220
It really depends on the shape.

302
00:14:34.220 --> 00:14:37.220
On how the device

303
00:14:37.220 --> 00:14:41.220
or object is exposed to the wind stream.

304
00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:43.310
Then we have air density in there.

305
00:14:43.310 --> 00:14:44.310
With the rho —

306
00:14:44.310 --> 00:14:45.310
above the P.

307
00:14:45.310 --> 00:14:47.310
Air density is of course also very important.

308
00:14:47.310 --> 00:14:50.310
At several different altitudes we don't have the same air density —

309
00:14:50.310 --> 00:14:52.310
if we're up at 2000 metres,

310
00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:55.310
because of course that affects drag too.

311
00:14:55.310 --> 00:14:57.790
Then we have speed.

312
00:14:57.790 --> 00:15:00.790
Careful, speed is always squared.

313
00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:03.790
It has an influence as a square.

314
00:15:03.790 --> 00:15:05.790
We'll come back to that

315
00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:07.790
in detail,

316
00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:10.080
for us with the paraglider.

317
00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:12.080
And S is also still in there,

318
00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:14.080
that's the area of the object.

319
00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:16.690
For lift it's exactly the same.

320
00:15:16.690 --> 00:15:17.690
Only the B-value,

321
00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:19.690
the coefficient, changes there.

322
00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:22.690
The remaining factors are the same.

323
00:15:22.690 --> 00:15:26.170
Lift has a different B-value,

324
00:15:26.170 --> 00:15:30.170
and that's what influences how lift behaves.

325
00:15:30.170 --> 00:15:32.580
Or the force that arises

326
00:15:32.580 --> 00:15:34.580
and then gives lift.

327
00:15:34.580 --> 00:15:39.370
On the SHV exam question

328
00:15:39.370 --> 00:15:41.370
you can find this again and again —

329
00:15:41.370 --> 00:15:43.370
what happens

330
00:15:43.370 --> 00:15:46.370
if you have a certain area.

331
00:15:46.370 --> 00:15:49.370
It causes a certain drag in the wind.

332
00:15:49.370 --> 00:15:50.370
What happens

333
00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:52.370
if you double or halve the area?

334
00:15:52.370 --> 00:15:55.370
And that's always relatively simple.

335
00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:56.370
It's always linear.

336
00:15:56.370 --> 00:15:59.370
If you double the area of an object,

337
00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:01.370
the drag also doubles.

338
00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:02.370
If you halve it,

339
00:16:02.370 --> 00:16:04.370
the drag halves.

340
00:16:04.370 --> 00:16:06.370
If you halve the air density,

341
00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:08.370
because you go way, way higher,

342
00:16:08.370 --> 00:16:10.370
for example when you launch the paraglider,

343
00:16:10.370 --> 00:16:13.660
then the drag also halves.

344
00:16:13.660 --> 00:16:15.660
A really big exclamation mark

345
00:16:15.660 --> 00:16:17.660
is for speed.

346
00:16:17.660 --> 00:16:19.660
When it comes to speed,

347
00:16:19.660 --> 00:16:21.660
things always behave as a square.

348
00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:23.660
So if speed doubles,

349
00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:26.660
then all forces quadruple.

350
00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:29.660
If speed triples,

351
00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:32.660
then all forces become nine times as large.

352
00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:34.660
I'm always urging this for a question.

353
00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:37.660
Don't let the urgency lure you in,

354
00:16:37.660 --> 00:16:39.660
just clicking quickly,

355
00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:40.660
but look carefully:

356
00:16:40.660 --> 00:16:42.660
is it about some factor

357
00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:45.660
or about speed in the question.

358
00:16:45.660 --> 00:16:48.820
Very important not to mix it up.

359
00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:51.040
Here's an example right now.

360
00:16:51.040 --> 00:16:54.040
I won't read out the whole question now,

361
00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:57.040
but if we have 30 km/h

362
00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:01.040
and in the second case we have 90 km/h,

363
00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:04.040
then that's a tripling of the speed,

364
00:17:04.040 --> 00:17:06.040
of the wind speed,

365
00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:09.040
and a ninefold increase of the drag.

366
00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:12.040
So from 100 Newtons it doesn't become 300 Newtons,

367
00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:13.040
as you might think,

368
00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:15.040
but 900.

369
00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:21.780
In the meteorology course

370
00:17:21.780 --> 00:17:24.780
we'll learn some very

371
00:17:24.780 --> 00:17:28.780
important info about our planet's atmosphere.

372
00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:32.780
For the paraglider, this affects us

373
00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:34.780
in that higher up,

374
00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:36.780
we have less air density

375
00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:39.780
and there are fewer air particles around.

376
00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:42.780
And our wing has to move faster, or through the air,

377
00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:44.780
to produce the same lift.

378
00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:45.780
That means,

379
00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:46.780
very simply put,

380
00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:48.780
you need a higher takeoff speed.

381
00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:52.130
We can see from this curve

382
00:17:52.130 --> 00:17:55.130
that air pressure decreases with altitude.

383
00:17:56.130 --> 00:18:00.510
At 5,500 metres it's already only half as large,

384
00:18:00.510 --> 00:18:02.510
and along with air pressure,

385
00:18:02.510 --> 00:18:04.510
air density also decreases,

386
00:18:04.510 --> 00:18:07.510
which appears in our formula too.

387
00:18:07.510 --> 00:18:11.510
Air density first halves at 6,600 metres,

388
00:18:11.510 --> 00:18:12.510
it halves,

389
00:18:12.510 --> 00:18:14.510
so watch out not to mix them up.

390
00:18:14.510 --> 00:18:16.510
But ultimately it doesn't matter,

391
00:18:16.510 --> 00:18:19.510
whether it's now 5,500 metres or 6,500 metres,

392
00:18:19.510 --> 00:18:21.510
for the theory exam of course it does.

393
00:18:21.510 --> 00:18:25.510
But in practice it has the same effect.

394
00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:27.510
The effect is

395
00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:29.510
that air density decreases.

396
00:18:29.510 --> 00:18:30.510
There are fewer air particles.

397
00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:34.830
And somehow we have to generate our lift,

398
00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.830
because the problem is,

399
00:18:36.830 --> 00:18:38.830
if we look at the formula,

400
00:18:38.830 --> 00:18:40.830
the drag coefficient

401
00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:41.830
stays the same.

402
00:18:42.830 --> 00:18:45.410
The area of our wing

403
00:18:45.410 --> 00:18:47.410
stays the same.

404
00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:49.410
Our weight stays the same.

405
00:18:49.410 --> 00:18:50.410
That means lift,

406
00:18:50.410 --> 00:18:51.410
which we can reduce

407
00:18:51.410 --> 00:18:52.410
by going through the air.

408
00:18:52.410 --> 00:18:53.410
It stays the same.

409
00:18:53.410 --> 00:18:56.410
But our density is only about half as much,

410
00:18:56.410 --> 00:18:58.410
or maybe 30% less.

411
00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:01.410
That means, to get the lift up front

412
00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:03.410
back to the same value.

413
00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:05.410
If somehow,

414
00:19:05.410 --> 00:19:07.410
we can only compensate for this one way,

415
00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:09.410
we have to make up for it through speed.

416
00:19:09.410 --> 00:19:10.410
It comes in handy for us

417
00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:12.410
that speed is squared.

418
00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:13.410
That means,

419
00:19:13.410 --> 00:19:15.410
at half air density

420
00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:18.410
we don't have to run twice as fast.

421
00:19:18.410 --> 00:19:20.410
Just the square root of two.

422
00:19:20.410 --> 00:19:23.410
Now this is getting a bit much already.

423
00:19:23.410 --> 00:19:24.410
It's mathematical.

424
00:19:24.410 --> 00:19:26.410
But it means,

425
00:19:26.410 --> 00:19:28.410
if you launch from a high mountain

426
00:19:28.410 --> 00:19:29.410
you have to be aware,

427
00:19:29.410 --> 00:19:31.410
you have to run much faster.

428
00:19:31.410 --> 00:19:33.410
Which usually goes against the grain a bit,

429
00:19:33.410 --> 00:19:35.410
because you might already be tired,

430
00:19:35.410 --> 00:19:37.410
you might have hiked up,

431
00:19:37.410 --> 00:19:39.410
you might be launching in deep snow,

432
00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:41.410
out front it might be steep,

433
00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:43.410
but just keep it in mind:

434
00:19:43.410 --> 00:19:44.410
you need more speed,

435
00:19:44.410 --> 00:19:45.410
more speed

436
00:19:45.410 --> 00:19:47.410
also means a longer running distance.

437
00:19:47.410 --> 00:19:49.730
On the other side

438
00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:51.730
you shouldn't forget the advantages.

439
00:19:51.730 --> 00:19:55.730
You can handle a bit more wind

440
00:19:55.730 --> 00:19:57.730
when the air density decreases.

441
00:19:57.730 --> 00:19:59.730
So there are advantages too,

442
00:19:59.730 --> 00:20:01.730
that you can maybe still launch up there in a 30 km/h wind

443
00:20:01.730 --> 00:20:03.730
as a beginner,

444
00:20:04.730 --> 00:20:06.730
whereas down at 1500 metres in 30 km/h

445
00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:08.730
it would already be quite demanding

446
00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:12.730
and probably not possible at launch any more.

447
00:20:12.730 --> 00:20:18.770
Now we can quickly move on

448
00:20:18.770 --> 00:20:20.770
to these drag coefficients,

449
00:20:20.770 --> 00:20:21.770
the cw values,

450
00:20:21.770 --> 00:20:22.770
as I said,

451
00:20:22.770 --> 00:20:24.770
it really depends on what object

452
00:20:24.770 --> 00:20:25.770
we have,

453
00:20:25.770 --> 00:20:27.770
whether it's the wing or something else.

454
00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:30.120
What's important is

455
00:20:30.120 --> 00:20:34.050
when you compare objects

456
00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:35.050
with each other,

457
00:20:35.050 --> 00:20:36.050
you always

458
00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:38.050
assume the same frontal area.

459
00:20:38.050 --> 00:20:40.050
Here,

460
00:20:40.050 --> 00:20:41.050
when you compare these,

461
00:20:41.050 --> 00:20:43.620
they all have a certain drag,

462
00:20:43.620 --> 00:20:45.620
when the air flows around them,

463
00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:46.620
but some of them,

464
00:20:46.620 --> 00:20:48.620
have much more than the others.

465
00:20:48.620 --> 00:20:50.620
And that comes down to the cw value,

466
00:20:50.620 --> 00:20:51.620
as I said,

467
00:20:51.620 --> 00:20:52.620
also depending on the shape.

468
00:20:52.620 --> 00:20:53.620
So for example a half-shell,

469
00:20:53.620 --> 00:20:55.620
is 30 times,

470
00:21:07.620 --> 00:21:09.780
(unclear)

471
00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:30.200
(unclear)

472
00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:42.940
It always goes — driven by gravity — towards something

473
00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:44.940
that offers the least resistance.

474
00:21:44.940 --> 00:21:48.940
And if you look very closely, it actually looks like a raindrop.

475
00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:52.940
And the raindrop can't just fall from the sky like a flat board either,

476
00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:54.940
but it also doesn't fall straight from the sky,

477
00:21:54.940 --> 00:21:58.940
in a way that offers the least possible drag and the most efficient

478
00:21:58.940 --> 00:22:00.940
shape it can.

479
00:22:00.940 --> 00:22:05.940
And that's been put to use long ago

480
00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:07.940
with the anemometer.

481
00:22:07.940 --> 00:22:09.940
They use half-shells,

482
00:22:09.940 --> 00:22:14.160
because if you used spheres or some sliding shapes,

483
00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:16.160
for an anemometer,

484
00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:18.160
they wouldn't move easily,

485
00:22:18.160 --> 00:22:20.160
since the force would be the same on all sides.

486
00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:22.160
But because they are half-shells,

487
00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:24.160
the wind that blows into here

488
00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:26.160
causes much more drag

489
00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:28.160
than the wind that blows over here,

490
00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:31.160
and so the little wheel starts to turn,

491
00:22:31.160 --> 00:22:35.160
and that's then converted into a certain wind speed.

492
00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:39.280
Here too, the formula squared,

493
00:22:39.280 --> 00:22:42.270
is what gives the drag.

494
00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:46.130
When we fly,

495
00:22:46.130 --> 00:22:50.130
we constantly have certain angle-of-attack changes.

496
00:22:50.130 --> 00:22:52.130
Normally, if you just fly the wing,

497
00:22:52.130 --> 00:22:55.130
you fly at trim speed,

498
00:22:55.130 --> 00:22:57.130
or at the angle of attack

499
00:22:57.130 --> 00:22:58.130
the wing is built with,

500
00:22:58.130 --> 00:23:02.130
or — depending on age, or when it ages and the line lengths

501
00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:03.130
are no longer quite right,

502
00:23:03.130 --> 00:23:05.130
then the wing's angle gets a bit larger.

503
00:23:05.130 --> 00:23:07.130
But we can influence it ourselves,

504
00:23:07.130 --> 00:23:10.130
for example by braking or accelerating.

505
00:23:10.130 --> 00:23:12.130
When you brake, the angle of attack gets bigger,

506
00:23:12.130 --> 00:23:16.130
because for example you pull down the edge, and the connecting line

507
00:23:16.130 --> 00:23:19.130
from the rearmost point to the foremost point,

508
00:23:19.130 --> 00:23:23.130
you change massively,

509
00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:26.130
you change the flight speed and you sink more,

510
00:23:26.130 --> 00:23:29.130
and the angle of attack gets bigger.

511
00:23:30.130 --> 00:23:32.610
It looks roughly like this:

512
00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:34.610
the wing flies slowly,

513
00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:36.610
for example the ca and cw values,

514
00:23:36.610 --> 00:23:37.610
get bigger.

515
00:23:37.610 --> 00:23:38.610
It's very important,

516
00:23:38.610 --> 00:23:40.610
also for the theory exam,

517
00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:41.610
to remember:

518
00:23:41.610 --> 00:23:43.610
when the wing's angle of attack gets bigger,

519
00:23:43.610 --> 00:23:45.610
the values grow,

520
00:23:45.610 --> 00:23:47.500
and vice versa,

521
00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:49.500
when you accelerate the wing,

522
00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:52.500
and the angle of attack gets smaller,

523
00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:55.500
then the ca and cw values get smaller.

524
00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:57.950
Very important is

525
00:23:57.950 --> 00:23:58.950
to know:

526
00:23:58.950 --> 00:24:00.950
we're always talking about steady glide.

527
00:24:00.950 --> 00:24:01.950
So,

528
00:24:01.950 --> 00:24:03.950
whether we're heavily braking,

529
00:24:03.950 --> 00:24:05.950
or accelerated,

530
00:24:05.950 --> 00:24:07.950
it's always stationary and the wing

531
00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:09.950
is flying on a line,

532
00:24:09.950 --> 00:24:11.950
in a stable state.

533
00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:13.950
And then in steady glide,

534
00:24:13.950 --> 00:24:15.950
the yellow arrow and the violet arrow,

535
00:24:15.950 --> 00:24:17.950
so our force,

536
00:24:17.950 --> 00:24:19.950
our aerodynamic resultant

537
00:24:19.950 --> 00:24:21.950
and the weight force, are always equal in size.

538
00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:23.950
If you come from full speed

539
00:24:23.950 --> 00:24:25.950
and brake,

540
00:24:25.950 --> 00:24:26.950
we know

541
00:24:26.950 --> 00:24:29.950
that the wing at first

542
00:24:29.950 --> 00:24:31.950
(unclear)

543
00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:33.950
(unclear)

544
00:24:33.950 --> 00:24:35.950
(unclear)

545
00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:37.950
(unclear)

546
00:24:37.950 --> 00:24:39.950
(unclear)

547
00:24:39.950 --> 00:24:41.950
(unclear)

548
00:24:41.950 --> 00:24:54.430
(unclear)

549
00:24:54.430 --> 00:24:56.390
(unclear)

550
00:24:56.390 --> 00:24:58.390
For us on the wing,

551
00:24:58.390 --> 00:25:01.770
the stagnation point is the point

552
00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:03.770
going onto the underside.

553
00:25:03.770 --> 00:25:07.770
It's the apex where the flow divides.

554
00:25:07.770 --> 00:25:09.770
And this point shifts of course,

555
00:25:09.770 --> 00:25:11.770
it doesn't always stay the same.

556
00:25:11.770 --> 00:25:16.090
It also has to do with the angle of attack.

557
00:25:16.090 --> 00:25:21.090
If I increase the angle of attack here,

558
00:25:21.090 --> 00:25:25.090
the point wanders further to the rear.

559
00:25:25.090 --> 00:25:27.090
And now you can also see why

560
00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:30.090
the paraglider's cell openings

561
00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:32.090
are in the front-lower area

562
00:25:32.090 --> 00:25:34.090
and not just straight at the front or on top,

563
00:25:34.090 --> 00:25:36.090
because in that area,

564
00:25:36.090 --> 00:25:38.090
where we actually fly,

565
00:25:38.090 --> 00:25:42.180
we have our stagnation point pretty consistently

566
00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:43.180
in this area,

567
00:25:43.180 --> 00:25:45.180
where the cell openings also are, which makes perfect sense.

568
00:25:45.180 --> 00:25:49.630
The separation point behaves exactly the opposite way.

569
00:25:49.630 --> 00:25:51.630
So, when you brake more,

570
00:25:51.630 --> 00:25:53.630
then the separation point moves —

571
00:25:53.630 --> 00:25:55.630
the flow no longer follows the profile,

572
00:25:55.630 --> 00:25:57.630
ever further forward,

573
00:25:57.690 --> 00:25:59.630
with a bit of airflow.

574
00:25:59.630 --> 00:26:01.630
Until eventually the whole top tears off,

575
00:26:01.630 --> 00:26:03.630
and we no longer have any lift,

576
00:26:03.630 --> 00:26:05.630
we're stalled,

577
00:26:05.630 --> 00:26:07.630
and we're in a full stall.

578
00:26:07.630 --> 00:26:11.040
Right, that's it for that —

579
00:26:11.040 --> 00:26:14.040
what happens with the stagnation point and the separation point

580
00:26:14.040 --> 00:26:17.040
when you change the angle of attack

581
00:26:17.040 --> 00:26:19.040
and brake hard.

582
00:26:19.040 --> 00:26:23.030
Then we can move on to wingtip vortices and drag.

583
00:26:23.030 --> 00:26:25.030
Now we're getting heavily into drag,

584
00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:26.030
let's look —

585
00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:27.030
it's a whole topic.

586
00:26:27.030 --> 00:26:30.030
We'll look at how drag is roughly distributed on the paraglider,

587
00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:33.160
across the whole flying system.

588
00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:35.160
Profile drag,

589
00:26:35.160 --> 00:26:36.160
as you can see here,

590
00:26:36.160 --> 00:26:38.160
is about 20 percent.

591
00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:40.160
Lines are about 20 percent.

592
00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:42.160
Pilot is about 20 percent.

593
00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:44.160
And the largest part —

594
00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:47.160
it's a bit difficult to picture,

595
00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:48.160
because it's there,

596
00:26:48.160 --> 00:26:49.160
but you can't actually see it.

597
00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:51.160
It's induced drag.

598
00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:53.160
And induced drag

599
00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:55.160
is created at the wingtip,

600
00:26:55.160 --> 00:26:59.160
because we have high pressure and low pressure.

601
00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:01.380
And the pressures want to equalise,

602
00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:04.380
they want to balance out somehow.

603
00:27:04.380 --> 00:27:09.380
An imbalance is never good in nature or in physics.

604
00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:11.380
Things always want to equalise somehow.

605
00:27:11.380 --> 00:27:14.380
And at the wingtip you get turbulence.

606
00:27:14.380 --> 00:27:17.380
Which can be quite strong sometimes,

607
00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:20.380
so if you fly with a paraglider

608
00:27:20.380 --> 00:27:22.380
very close behind another one,

609
00:27:22.380 --> 00:27:23.380
then you'll notice

610
00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:25.380
how it shakes you,

611
00:27:25.380 --> 00:27:26.380
on landing approach,

612
00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:27.380
definitely not recommended

613
00:27:27.380 --> 00:27:28.380
for new pilots to fly behind

614
00:27:28.380 --> 00:27:30.380
and better keep some distance.

615
00:27:30.380 --> 00:27:31.380
It would be

616
00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:33.380
if the aircraft is

617
00:27:33.380 --> 00:27:34.380
above the paraglider,

618
00:27:34.380 --> 00:27:36.380
or a Jumbo jet.

619
00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:39.380
It's pretty heavy and they're the wingtip vortices.

620
00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:40.610
That means,

621
00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:42.610
if you want to land,

622
00:27:42.610 --> 00:27:44.610
flying behind a tandem,

623
00:27:44.610 --> 00:27:45.610
be very careful,

624
00:27:45.610 --> 00:27:48.610
because the vortices are noticeably bigger,

625
00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:50.610
than with a solo wing.

626
00:27:50.610 --> 00:27:52.630
Now,

627
00:27:52.630 --> 00:27:53.630
our goal,

628
00:27:53.630 --> 00:27:54.630
as I said at the beginning,

629
00:27:54.630 --> 00:27:55.630
is the ideal —

630
00:27:55.630 --> 00:27:56.630
because we want

631
00:27:56.630 --> 00:27:57.630
to have less drag,

632
00:27:57.630 --> 00:27:58.630
more lift.

633
00:27:58.630 --> 00:28:01.630
How can we get closer to that?

634
00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:02.630
Looking at the profile,

635
00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:04.630
we can take this a bit further.

636
00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:05.630
Here,

637
00:28:05.630 --> 00:28:07.630
as you've seen,

638
00:28:07.630 --> 00:28:08.630
the wing has

639
00:28:08.630 --> 00:28:10.630
all these cell bumps,

640
00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:12.630
these waves and bulges,

641
00:28:12.630 --> 00:28:13.630
where actually,

642
00:28:13.630 --> 00:28:14.630
if you look at aircraft,

643
00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:15.630
where the surface is nice and smooth,

644
00:28:15.630 --> 00:28:17.630
this is actually quite inefficient

645
00:28:17.630 --> 00:28:19.630
and not very favourable.

646
00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:21.980
That's why high-performance wings,

647
00:28:21.980 --> 00:28:23.980
or also intermediate wings,

648
00:28:23.980 --> 00:28:24.980
the further up you go,

649
00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:25.980
the more

650
00:28:25.980 --> 00:28:26.980
the difficulty class,

651
00:28:26.980 --> 00:28:28.980
the more cells the wing has.

652
00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:30.980
And the cells essentially mean

653
00:28:30.980 --> 00:28:32.980
that the waves

654
00:28:32.980 --> 00:28:33.980
are as flat as possible,

655
00:28:33.980 --> 00:28:36.980
so smaller waves rather

656
00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:38.980
than large bulges,

657
00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:40.980
we get much closer

658
00:28:40.980 --> 00:28:42.980
to the ideal profile we're aiming for.

659
00:28:42.980 --> 00:28:45.340
But this also requires

660
00:28:45.340 --> 00:28:46.340
that you can master the wing,

661
00:28:46.340 --> 00:28:47.340
handle it,

662
00:28:47.340 --> 00:28:49.340
because it's just much harder

663
00:28:49.340 --> 00:28:50.340
to fly.

664
00:28:50.340 --> 00:28:51.340
Induced drag,

665
00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:53.340
you reduce through aspect ratio (span).

666
00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:55.340
On aircraft you also have winglets,

667
00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:56.340
which you can see,

668
00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:23.620
the next thing is the lines.

669
00:29:23.620 --> 00:29:25.620
Here, of course, in the ideal case

670
00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:28.620
you want as few lines as possible and as thin as possible,

671
00:29:28.620 --> 00:29:31.620
which again brings with it

672
00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:32.620
that things get tight,

673
00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:34.620
that it's more demanding

674
00:29:34.620 --> 00:29:35.620
to fly,

675
00:29:35.620 --> 00:29:36.620
in case of disturbance,

676
00:29:36.620 --> 00:29:38.620
and so on.

677
00:29:38.620 --> 00:29:39.620
So you've seen,

678
00:29:39.620 --> 00:29:40.620
all the factors

679
00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:42.880
basically come down to this:

680
00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:43.880
the wing becomes harder

681
00:29:43.880 --> 00:29:44.880
to fly.

682
00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:46.880
And needs much more know-how.

683
00:29:46.880 --> 00:29:49.200
And last but not least,

684
00:29:49.200 --> 00:29:50.200
pilot,

685
00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:52.200
the harness,

686
00:29:52.200 --> 00:29:54.200
of course also makes a huge difference,

687
00:29:54.200 --> 00:29:56.200
whether we sit upright,

688
00:29:56.200 --> 00:29:58.200
and present a large frontal surface to the wind,

689
00:29:58.200 --> 00:30:00.200
or whether we lie down,

690
00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:01.200
are as small as possible,

691
00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:02.200
this also

692
00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:05.200
makes a few percent difference,

693
00:30:05.200 --> 00:30:06.200
where you can optimise.

694
00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:08.200
I've drawn this quickly,

695
00:30:08.200 --> 00:30:09.200
what a prone harness

696
00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:10.200
approximately in the wind tunnel,

697
00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:12.200
could look like.

698
00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:13.200
So here too,

699
00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:14.200
in the front,

700
00:30:14.200 --> 00:30:15.200
as round as possible,

701
00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:17.200
so the air particles

702
00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:18.200
split nicely,

703
00:30:18.200 --> 00:30:20.200
and flow around,

704
00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:21.200
like with a raindrop,

705
00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:22.200
and run along,

706
00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:24.200
nicely behind.

707
00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:26.460
In the ideal case

708
00:30:26.460 --> 00:30:28.460
the harness has

709
00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:30.460
a kind of tapered point at the back,

710
00:30:30.460 --> 00:30:31.460
and it's not

711
00:30:31.460 --> 00:30:32.460
any sharp edges,

712
00:30:32.460 --> 00:30:33.460
where the flow tears off,

713
00:30:33.460 --> 00:30:34.460
but really runs

714
00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:35.460
into the slit,

715
00:30:35.460 --> 00:30:37.460
or down to the tapered back end,

716
00:30:37.460 --> 00:30:38.460
and then goes,

717
00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:39.460
well,

718
00:30:39.460 --> 00:30:40.460
rejoins at the back.

719
00:30:40.460 --> 00:30:41.460
So that at the back

720
00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:43.460
as little turbulence as possible

721
00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:44.460
occurs.

722
00:30:44.460 --> 00:30:46.460
And that way you can also

723
00:30:46.460 --> 00:30:47.460
get the maximum out of it.

724
00:30:47.460 --> 00:30:48.460
And by the way,

725
00:30:48.460 --> 00:30:49.460
it's not just

726
00:30:49.460 --> 00:30:51.460
that it's extremely comfortable,

727
00:30:51.460 --> 00:30:52.460
and warm too.

728
00:30:52.460 --> 00:30:54.460
Aerodynamically it really is

729
00:30:54.460 --> 00:30:56.460
quite a big difference.

730
00:30:56.460 --> 00:30:58.680
But also again,

731
00:30:58.680 --> 00:31:01.100
more demanding to fly.

732
00:31:01.100 --> 00:31:03.100
Now we can clear up the terminology.

733
00:31:03.100 --> 00:31:07.100
First we talk about wingspan,

734
00:31:07.100 --> 00:31:09.100
and what's also important to know

735
00:31:09.100 --> 00:31:12.100
is that all the measurements

736
00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:14.100
we're now discussing,

737
00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:16.100
for the paraglider always come

738
00:31:16.100 --> 00:31:18.100
as laid-out and projected.

739
00:31:18.100 --> 00:31:20.100
Because laid out,

740
00:31:20.100 --> 00:31:21.100
the wing is

741
00:31:21.100 --> 00:31:22.100
much bigger,

742
00:31:22.100 --> 00:31:23.100
than afterward,

743
00:31:23.100 --> 00:31:24.100
when it's in the air.

744
00:31:24.100 --> 00:31:25.100
So the outermost

745
00:31:25.100 --> 00:31:26.100
two points,

746
00:31:26.100 --> 00:31:27.100
are in the air

747
00:31:27.100 --> 00:31:28.100
a bit smaller apart,

748
00:31:28.100 --> 00:31:31.100
and what's

749
00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:32.100
aerodynamically

750
00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:33.100
interesting,

751
00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:34.100
and the area

752
00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:35.100
where it's in the air

753
00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:36.100
measured,

754
00:31:36.100 --> 00:31:37.100
above the head,

755
00:31:37.100 --> 00:31:39.100
and producing lift,

756
00:31:39.100 --> 00:31:41.100
is always the projected area.

757
00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:42.100
But here,

758
00:31:42.100 --> 00:31:43.100
sometimes,

759
00:31:43.100 --> 00:31:44.100
you have to be careful

760
00:31:44.100 --> 00:31:46.100
that you're using the same measure,

761
00:31:46.100 --> 00:31:47.100
if someone says

762
00:31:47.100 --> 00:31:49.100
yes, you have 20 square metres,

763
00:31:49.100 --> 00:31:51.100
and then someone says,

764
00:31:51.100 --> 00:31:52.100
yes, the 18,

765
00:31:52.100 --> 00:31:54.100
and if you're not talking about the same measure,

766
00:31:54.100 --> 00:31:55.100
or about the same,

767
00:31:55.100 --> 00:31:56.100
yes,

768
00:31:56.100 --> 00:31:58.100
then under some circumstances

769
00:31:58.100 --> 00:31:59.100
you're describing

770
00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:00.320
the same wing,

771
00:32:00.320 --> 00:32:02.320
because one is talking about the laid-out,

772
00:32:02.320 --> 00:32:03.320
span or area,

773
00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:05.320
and the other the projected value.

774
00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:07.320
Now we come to wing chord.

775
00:32:07.320 --> 00:32:09.320
Here we always talk

776
00:32:09.320 --> 00:32:11.320
about the mean wing chord,

777
00:32:11.320 --> 00:32:13.320
because the wing chord at the stabiliser

778
00:32:13.320 --> 00:32:14.320
or at the wingtip,

779
00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:16.320
is much smaller than in the middle.

780
00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:17.320
And that's why

781
00:32:17.320 --> 00:32:19.320
we use the average

782
00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:20.320
and call that

783
00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:22.320
the mean wing chord.

784
00:32:22.320 --> 00:32:24.900
And aspect ratio,

785
00:32:24.900 --> 00:32:25.900
is

786
00:32:25.900 --> 00:32:26.900
what actually makes a wing

787
00:32:26.900 --> 00:32:28.900
more efficient,

788
00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:29.900
because,

789
00:32:29.900 --> 00:32:30.900
as we've seen,

790
00:32:30.900 --> 00:32:31.900
induced drag,

791
00:32:31.900 --> 00:32:32.900
is the biggest drag,

792
00:32:32.900 --> 00:32:33.900
and with aspect ratio

793
00:32:33.900 --> 00:32:34.900
you can actually,

794
00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:35.900
reduce that,

795
00:32:35.900 --> 00:32:36.900
it's the ratio

796
00:32:36.900 --> 00:32:37.900
of the span

797
00:32:37.900 --> 00:32:40.250
to the mean wing chord.

798
00:32:40.250 --> 00:32:42.250
Now the mean wing chord,

799
00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:44.250
you can't just measure directly.

800
00:32:44.250 --> 00:32:45.250
It has to be a value

801
00:32:45.250 --> 00:32:47.250
that the manufacturer provides.

802
00:32:47.250 --> 00:32:48.250
You can,

803
00:32:48.250 --> 00:32:50.250
if you look at the fraction,

804
00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:52.250
whether the span

805
00:32:52.250 --> 00:32:54.250
divided by mean wing chord.

806
00:32:54.250 --> 00:32:56.250
Average,

807
00:32:56.250 --> 00:32:56.290
you can expand the fraction

808
00:32:56.290 --> 00:32:58.500
as well,

809
00:32:58.500 --> 00:33:00.500
with span on top,

810
00:33:00.500 --> 00:33:01.500
span on the bottom,

811
00:33:01.500 --> 00:33:02.500
and then

812
00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:04.500
you get span

813
00:33:04.500 --> 00:33:06.500
squared, divided by area.

814
00:33:06.500 --> 00:33:07.500
So either

815
00:33:07.500 --> 00:33:10.500
span divided by mean wing chord

816
00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:13.500
or span squared divided by area.

817
00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:14.500
Divided by area.

818
00:33:14.500 --> 00:33:16.500
Divided by area.

819
00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:17.500
Divided by area.

820
00:33:17.500 --> 00:33:18.500
Divided by area.

821
00:33:18.500 --> 00:33:23.220
And that's the aspect ratio.

822
00:33:23.220 --> 00:33:25.220
Or it's slenderness.

823
00:33:25.220 --> 00:33:27.220
Then we have one more clarification.

824
00:33:27.220 --> 00:33:28.220
Projected area,

825
00:33:28.220 --> 00:33:30.220
we'd already covered through the riser side

826
00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:32.220
via the lines.

827
00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:33.220
Or — better said,

828
00:33:33.220 --> 00:33:35.220
or the projected area

829
00:33:35.220 --> 00:33:37.220
is of course much further along.

830
00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:38.220
If you're not at the landing site,

831
00:33:38.220 --> 00:33:39.220
for example at the dealer,

832
00:33:39.220 --> 00:33:41.220
and want to see this wing,

833
00:33:41.220 --> 00:33:42.220
how big is its shadow.

834
00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:45.660
So that should explain the projected area.
